Build a full-featured collaborative online whiteboard application inspired by Excalidraw. The application should provide an infinite canvas where users can create hand-drawn-style diagrams, sketches, wireframes, flowcharts, visual notes, and brainstorming boards. Do not copy Excalidraw’s branding, logo, name, proprietary assets, or exact UI styling; instead, create an original but familiar whiteboard experience with comparable functionality.

The app should include an infinite pan-and-zoom canvas with smooth performance. Users must be able to pan using a hand tool, mouse drag, trackpad gestures, or spacebar-drag behavior. The canvas should support zoom in, zoom out, reset zoom, zoom-to-fit, and viewport navigation. Add optional grid mode, background color selection, and light/dark/system theme support.

Implement a drawing toolbar with these tools: selection, hand/pan, rectangle, diamond, ellipse, arrow, straight line, freehand pencil, text, image insertion, eraser, and a “more tools” menu. Each tool should have intuitive keyboard shortcuts similar to common whiteboard tools, including number-key shortcuts and letter shortcuts. The selected tool should optionally remain active through a lock-tool toggle.

Create a robust scene model where every canvas object is represented as editable JSON. Supported element types should include rectangles, diamonds, ellipses, arrows, lines, freehand strokes, text blocks, images, frames, and groups. Each element should store position, size, rotation, z-index, style, opacity, roughness/sloppiness, stroke color, background color, fill style, stroke width, stroke style, text properties, links, metadata, and version history fields required for collaboration.

Use a hand-drawn rendering style. Shapes should look naturally sketched rather than perfectly digital. Provide configurable style options including stroke color, background/fill color, transparent fill, hachure or sketch-style fill, solid fill, stroke width, solid/dashed/dotted stroke style, roughness/sloppiness, rounded corners, opacity, and edge style. Text should support font family choices such as handwritten, normal sans-serif, and monospace/code style, along with font size, color, alignment, and resizing.

Implement full object selection and editing. Users should be able to select one or multiple elements, drag them, resize them using handles, rotate them, duplicate them, delete them, group and ungroup them, lock/unlock them, align them, distribute them, reorder layers, bring forward, send backward, bring to front, and send to back. Add context menus for common actions. Support copy, paste, cut, undo, redo, and keyboard-driven editing.

Add smart arrows and connectors. Arrows should be editable, support different start/end arrowheads, connect visually to shapes, and update when connected shapes move. Support straight and elbow-style connectors if possible. Allow users to add labels or bound text to shapes and connectors.

Implement text editing directly on the canvas. Users should be able to click to create text, drag to create a text box, double-click to edit existing text, resize text boxes, bind text to shapes, unbind text, and add clickable links to text or elements.

Support image insertion. Users should be able to upload PNG, JPG, SVG, and WebP files, paste images from the clipboard, drag-and-drop images onto the canvas, resize images, crop or fit them if practical, and preserve image assets when saving or exporting the scene.

Create a reusable library system. Users should be able to save selected elements as reusable components, browse local libraries, insert library items into the canvas, import/export library files, and manage custom library collections. The library should work locally without requiring an account.

Implement local-first persistence. The app should automatically save the current scene to browser storage and warn users that browser storage may be cleared. Users must be able to save their work as an editable project file, such as `.whiteboard` or `.json`, and later load it back with all elements remaining editable. Include autosave, manual save, load from file, and clear scene features.

Add export functionality. Users should be able to export the full canvas or selected objects as PNG, SVG, and JSON. Export settings should include transparent background, padding, scale factor, include/exclude background, dark/light export mode, and copy-to-clipboard where supported. Ensure exported SVG and PNG preserve the hand-drawn style.

Implement real-time collaboration. Users should be able to create a collaborative room, share a link, and edit the same canvas with other users in real time. Show live cursors, user names or anonymous labels, presence indicators, and conflict-free synchronized updates. Collaboration should support encrypted room links or end-to-end encryption if feasible, so only people with the shared link can access the scene. The app should not require login for basic collaboration.

Add a command palette and help system. Users should be able to press a shortcut such as Ctrl/Cmd+/ to open a command palette for searching actions, tools, settings, and scene commands. Provide a keyboard shortcuts modal accessible with `?`. Include search within the scene by text content.

Design a clean, minimal interface. The UI should include a top-centered drawing toolbar, a left or contextual style panel when elements are selected, bottom-left zoom and undo/redo controls, a top-left menu for file/canvas actions, and a top-right share/collaboration button. The interface should be responsive and usable on desktop and tablets.

The application should include these menus and panels: file menu, canvas settings menu, contextual element style panel, layer/actions panel, library panel, collaboration/share dialog, export dialog, keyboard shortcuts modal, command palette, and context menu.

Implement accessibility and usability features. Provide keyboard navigation where possible, ARIA labels for controls, high-contrast modes, focus states, touch-friendly controls, clipboard support, drag-and-drop support, and clear error messages.

Use a modern technical stack. Prefer React with TypeScript for the frontend, a canvas/SVG rendering layer suitable for interactive drawing, Zustand or another lightweight state manager, localStorage/IndexedDB for local persistence, WebSockets or WebRTC for collaboration, and a backend such as Node.js with Express/Fastify or a serverless equivalent for room signaling and collaboration state. Keep the architecture modular so the canvas engine, rendering, tools, collaboration, persistence, and export systems are separated.

Suggested modules:

1. Canvas engine: viewport, zoom, pan, hit testing, selection, snapping, object transforms.
2. Element model: shape schemas, serialization, versioning, z-index, groups, assets.
3. Rendering engine: rough hand-drawn rendering, text rendering, image rendering, overlays.
4. Tool controller: selection, shapes, pencil, text, image, eraser, connector tools.
5. Style system: colors, fills, strokes, fonts, opacity, theme, background.
6. Persistence: autosave, save file, load file, IndexedDB/localStorage.
7. Export system: PNG, SVG, JSON, clipboard export.
8. Collaboration: shared rooms, live cursors, conflict handling, encrypted scene updates.
9. Library system: reusable components, import/export libraries.
10. UI shell: toolbar, panels, menus, modals, shortcuts, command palette.

Acceptance criteria:

- A user can open the app and draw shapes, arrows, text, freehand strokes, and images on an infinite canvas.
- All elements are editable after creation.
- The user can style objects with stroke, fill, roughness, opacity, font, and line options.
- The user can select, move, resize, rotate, group, duplicate, delete, and reorder objects.
- The user can save and reload an editable scene file.
- The user can export PNG, SVG, and JSON.
- The user can collaborate in real time through a shareable room link.
- The user can use keyboard shortcuts, undo/redo, zoom controls, and a command palette.
- The app works without login for core local drawing features.
- The app has an original brand and UI while providing functionality comparable to a modern collaborative sketch whiteboard.

Focus on creating a production-quality MVP first, then progressively add advanced features such as encrypted collaboration, library marketplace, presentation frames, cloud workspaces, comments, version history, advanced snapping, and AI-assisted diagram generation.
